const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why won't my Cairns aircon get below 24°C?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In tropical Cairns, the most common cause is a fouled condenser coil at the outdoor unit — salt and wet-season dust packing the fins, dropping heat rejection, and capping the cooling capacity at the moment ambient is hottest. The second most common is a fouled or mould-bloomed evaporator coil indoors restricting air flow. The third is a slow refrigerant leak the homeowner has been living with for months. We walk a six-point fault tree on every won't-cool call rather than guessing — half the time the fix is a deep coil clean, not a re-gas."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the right discharge-line temperature on a healthy system?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Discharge line temperature on a healthy R32 split running at 30-degree ambient should sit between 65 and 85 degrees C measured 150mm from the compressor on the discharge side. Below 60 suggests overcharge or a worn compressor not building head pressure. Above 95 suggests undercharge, a restriction, or a fouled condenser unable to reject heat. Discharge temperature is one of the fastest non-invasive diagnostics on a won't-cool call — we clip an infrared probe on, run the system for fifteen minutes, and the reading tells us where to look next."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does low refrigerant masquerade as 'old system needs replacing'?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A slowly leaking system loses cooling capacity gradually over months — you do not notice the day it dropped from 95 to 90 per cent, you only notice when it stops getting the room below 25 degrees in late January. Most homeowners conclude the system is worn out and start shopping for a new install. In reality the compressor is fine, the coils are fine, the system just needs the leak found, repaired, and a proper charge weighed in. We have rescued plenty of Cairns systems on the brink of replacement with a 700-dollar leak-and-recharge job instead of a 3,500-dollar new install."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When is it actually a compressor at end-of-life?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Compressor end-of-life shows up as low capacity with normal-or-high suction pressure, low head pressure, low current draw on the run leg, and warm discharge gas. Pressures stay flat-ish across the cycle when they should be moving. On an inverter compressor a failing internal valve plate looks identical. We confirm with a pressure-temperature analysis and a hot-stack reading. If the compressor is genuinely at end-of-life on a 10-plus-year Cairns system, replacement of the outdoor unit is usually more economic than a compressor swap because of labour and the cost of recovery and recharge on the full system."
      }
    }
  ]
};
